              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>Important:</strong> In Toronto, Mississauga, Brampton, Vaughan, Hamilton, and Oakville, you can only operate a short-term rental (under 28-30 days) from your primary home - the place where you actually live.
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>Investment properties, secondary homes, and vacation properties are <strong>not eligible</strong> for short-term rental licenses in these cities.</p>

          <h2 id="why-exists">Why This Rule Exists</h2>
          <p>GTA municipalities implemented the principal residence requirement for several reasons:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Housing supply concerns</strong> - Prevent investment properties from being converted to short-term rentals, reducing long-term housing availability</li>
            <li><strong>Neighbourhood stability</strong> - Maintain residential character in neighbourhoods by limiting commercial-style operations</li>
            <li><strong>Accountability</strong> - Ensure there's a local resident responsible for the property and guest behaviour</li>
            <li><strong>Tax base protection</strong> - Keep residential properties in residential use</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="gta-cities">GTA Cities & Their Rules</h2>
          <p>Here's a quick overview of how major GTA cities handle investment properties and short-term rentals:</p>

